Thinking Like Transformers

  • Paper by Gail Weiss, Yoav Goldberg, Eran Yahav
  • Blog by Sasha Rush and Gail Weiss

Transformers models are the foundation in which all deep learning approaches to text and code generation are built. There are countless explanations of what transformers do? in the sense of a description of the mathematical calculation at the heart of transformers.

However this calculation does not provide much intuition into the foundation calculations possible in this framework. An emerging area of research looks into the foundation computational blocks that transformers use, and how we, as mere mortals, can gain intuition to how transformers compute.

The paper Thinking like Transformers describes a computing framework for mimicking transformer calculations in a way that connects more closely to the discrete computation. This language RASP is a mini-programming language where every program compiles to a transformer representation.

For this blog post, I reimplement a variant of RASP, which we call RASPy.

def flip():
    length = (key(1) == query(1)).value(1)
    flip = (key(length - indices - 1) == query(indices)).value(tokens)
    return flip
flip()

Transformers as Code

The main idea of RASP is to define a formalism that mimics the expressivity of transformers. Well go through this by example, describing each construct by analogy to the aspect of the transformer it represents.

Inputs

The base layer of the transformer is the input fed to the model.

The symbol tokens represents the simplest transformer. It returns the tokens passed to the model. The default input is the sequence hello.

tokens

If we want to change the input to the model, we use the input method to pass in an alternative.

tokens.input([5, 2, 4, 5, 2, 2])

As with transformers, we cannot access the positions of these sequences directly. However, to mimic position embeddings, we have access to a sequence of indices.

indices
sop = indices
sop.input("goodbye")

Feed Forward Network

After the input layer, we reach the feed-forward network. At this stage we can apply mathematical operations to each element of the sequence independently.

We can apply simple operations. These apply to each element in the sequence.

tokens == "l"

Note that the result of these is not a sequence, but a full transformer model. Formally this is known as sequence op. Its a function from sequences to sequences.

model = tokens * 2  - 1
model.input([1, 2, 3, 5, 2])

Operations can combine multiple sequences. For example, functions of the tokens and the indices. We can think of these as being stored in different hidden dimensions of the activation at this layer.

model = tokens - 5 + indices
model.input([1, 2, 3, 5, 2])
(tokens == "l") | (indices == 1)

We provide a few helper functions to make it easier to write transforms. For example, where provides an if statement like construct

where((tokens == "h") | (tokens == "l"), tokens, "q")

And map lets us define our own operators, for instanc a string to int transform

atoi = tokens.map(lambda x: ord(x) - ord('0'))
atoi.input("31234")

When chaining these transforms, it is often easier to write as functions. For example the following applies where and then atoi and then adds 2.

def atoi(seq=tokens):
    return seq.map(lambda x: ord(x) - ord('0')) 

op = (atoi(where(tokens == "-", "0", tokens)) + 2)
op.input("02-13")

Attention Selectors

Things get more interesting when we start to apply attention. This allows routing of information between the different elements of the sequence.

We begin by defining notation for the keys and queries of the model. Keys and queries can be created directly from the transfoms defined above. For example if we want to define a key we call key.

key(tokens)

Similarly for query.

query(tokens)

Scalars can be used as keys or queries. They broadcast out to the length of tokens.

query(1)

By applying an operation between a keys and queries we create a selector. This corresponds to a binary matrix indicating which keys each query is attending to. Unlike in transformers, this attention matrix is unweighted.

eq = (key(tokens) == query(tokens))
eq

Some examples: A selector that is offset by 1.

offset = (key(indices) == query(indices - 1))
offset

A selector that attends to keys before the query in time.

before = key(indices) < query(indices)
before

A selector that attends to keys after the query in time.

after = key(indices) > query(indices)
after

Selectors can be merged with boolean operations. For example, this selector attends only to tokens before it in time with the same value. We show this by including both pairs of keys and values in the matrix.

before & eq

Using Attention

Given an attention selector we can provide a value to combine.

We sum up over the values that have a true value for their selector. (Note that this differs from RASP which aggregates with the mean)

This is easiest to see by examples.

(key(tokens) == query(tokens)).value(1)

Keys are to the left, Queries at the top, Values at the right, and the Output is below.

One useful operation will be to compute the length of a sequence. We do this by creating a select all attention and then adding up the value 1.

length = (key(1) == query(1)).value(1)
length = length.name("length")
length

Heres a more complex example. If we want to compute a windowed sum, we can create selectors on both sides and then apply an aggregation.

WINDOW=3
s1 = (key(indices) >= query(indices - WINDOW + 1))  
s1
s2 = (key(indices) <= query(indices))
s2
sel = s1 & s2
sel
sum2 = sel.value(tokens) 
sum2.input([1,3,2,2,2])

Heres a similar example with a cumulative sum.

def cumsum(seq=tokens):
    x = (before | (key(indices) == query(indices))).value(seq)
    return x.name("cumsum")
cumsum().input([3, 1, -2, 3, 1])

Layers

The language supports building up more complex functions by stacking attentions. This is done automatically by tracking the operations computed so far.

Here is a simple example that produces a 2-layer transform. The first corresponds to computing length and the second the cumulative sum.

x = cumsum(length - indices)
x.input([3, 2, 3, 5])

Coding with Transformers

Given this library of functions, we can write operations to accomplish surprisingly complex tasks. We will work our way up to fun problem: Can we produce a transformer that does basic aritmetic?. i.e.give a string 19492+23919 can we produce the correct output?

If you would rather do these on your own, we provide a version with this part of the notebook blank out.

Challenge 1: Select a given index

Produce a sequence where all the elements have the value at index i.

def index(i, seq=tokens):
    x = (key(indices) == query(i)).value(seq)
    return x.name("index")
index(1)

Challenge 2: Shift

Shift all of the tokens in a sequence to the right by i positions.

def shift(i=1, default="_", seq=tokens):
    x = (key(indices) == query(indices-i)).value(seq, default)
    return x.name("shift")
shift(2)

Challenge 3: Minimum

Compute the minimum values of the sequence. (This one starts to get harder. Our version uses 2 layers of attention.)

def minimum(seq=tokens):
    sel1 = before & (key(seq) == query(seq))
    sel2 = key(seq) < query(seq)
    less = (sel1 | sel2).value(1)
    x = (key(less) == query(0)).value(seq)
    return x.name("min")
minimum()([5,3,2,5,2])

Challenge 4: First Index

Compute the first index that has token q. (2 layers)

def first(q, seq=tokens):
    return minimum(where(seq == q, indices, 99))
first("l")

Challenge 5: Right Align

Right align a padded sequence e.g.ralign().inputs(xyz___) =xyz" (3 layers)

def ralign(default="-", sop=tokens):
    cutoff = length - first("_", sop)
    x = (key(indices) == query(indices - cutoff)).value(sop, default)
    return x.name("ralign")
ralign()("xyz__")

Challenge 6: Split

Split a sequence into two parts. (5 layers)

def split(v, i, sop=tokens):

    mid = first(v, sop)
    if i == 0:
        x = ralign("0", where(indices < mid, sop, "_"))
        return x
    else:
        x = where(indices > mid, sop, "0")
        return x
split("+", 1)("xyz+zyr")
split("+", 0)("xyz+zyr")

Challenge 6: Split

Replace special tokens < with the closest non < value to their right. (2 layers)

def slide(match, seq=tokens):
    x = cumsum(match) 
    y = ((key(x) == query(x + 1)) & (key(match) == query(True))).value(seq)
    seq =  where(match, seq, y)
    return seq.name("slide")
slide(tokens != "<").input("xxxh<<<l")

Challenge 7: Add

For this one you want to perform addition of two numbers. Here are the steps.

add().input(683+345)

  1. Split into parts. Convert to ints. Add

683+345 => [0, 0, 0, 9, 12, 8]

  1. Compute the carry terms. Three possibilities: 1 has carry, 0 no carry, < maybe has carry.

[0, 0, 0, 9, 12, 8] => 00<100

  1. Slide the carry coefficients

00<100" => 001100"

  1. Complete the addition.

Each of these is 1 line of code. The full system is 8 attentions.

def add(sop=tokens):
    # 0) Parse and add
    x = atoi(split("+", 0, sop)) + atoi(split("+", 1, sop))
    # 1) Check for carries 
    carry = shift(-1, "0", where(x > 9, "1", where(x == 9, "<", "0")))
    # 2) In parallel, slide carries to their column                                         
    carries = atoi(slide(carry != "<", carry))
    # 3) Add in carries.                                                                                  
    return (x + carries) % 10
add()("683+345")
683 + 345
1028
